}{\plain \fs24 \tab }{\plain \fs24 \b 121-124.}{\plain \fs24   The canto concludes with a simile that perfectly expresses Dante's ambivalent \softline
feelings about Brunetto.  He looks every bit the winner -- but he is in last place.  In the actual race \softline
run outside Verona, the runners ran naked, according to the early commentators; the winner \softline
received a piece of green cloth, while the one who finished last was given a rooster, which he had \softline
to carry back into the city with him as a sign of his disgrace and a cause of derisive taunts on the \softline
part of his townsmen.  The case can be made that Dante treats Brunetto in exactly both these \softline
ways.\par
}{\plain \fs24 \tab Two biblical texts are of interest here: 'The race is not to the swift, nor the battle to the \softline
